<link href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=4200&amp;p=6678#p6678"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[h1 element should only be allowed once]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=4200&amp;p=6678#p6678"><![CDATA[
Screen readers do read the headings. while i don't think they don't care if its a h1 or a h2, we as authors generally should.<br /><br />Implying that a navigation column is part of the main article, would be semantically incorrect. Its a independent section of the page. An example of as to where it would be considered &quot;correct&quot; to have multiple h1s.<br /><span style="font-style: italic">The nav element deals with this in a cleaner fashion.</span><br /><br />You are thinking as if a website was a newspaper, and seem to overlook the fact that a website is much more sophisticated.<br /><br />The old way of dealing with structural sectioning, would call for the need to use multiple h1's. The new way is to use the sectioning elements, in which case the numbering of the headers would be ignored, given that the (sectioning elements are used).<br /><br />Only parts such as a &quot;table of contents&quot; list could be considered part of the main article, and as such be indicated by h2, or perhaps an aside element.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=1729">BlueBoden</a> — Wed Feb 09, 2011 10:06 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
